    "# Lesson: Object-Oriented Game Development ‚Äì Whack-a-Mole\n",
    "\n",
    "In this lesson we will study how **Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** principles can be applied to build a fun game: **Whack-a-Mole**.  \n",
    "We will not just play the game, but *learn the design concepts behind it*, how the code is organized, and why OOP is powerful for games and larger software projects.\n",
    "\n",
    "This lesson combines:\n",
    "- **Teaching text** to explain programming ideas step by step.\n",
    "- **Code examples** in JavaScript.\n",
    "- **FRQ-style practice** scattered throughout to simulate AP CSP exam thinking.\n",
    "- **Connections to Big Ideas** (abstraction, data, algorithms, impact)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##  Learning Objectives\n",
    "By the end of this lesson, you should be able to:\n",
    "- Define and identify **OOP principles** (encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism, composition).\n",
    "- Explain how OOP helps organize complex programs like games.\n",
    "- Understand how **local storage** can persist data beyond runtime.\n",
    "- Analyze and modify code to meet new requirements (FRQs)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##  The Whack-a-Mole Concept\n",
    "In Whack-a-Mole, the computer manages a grid of *holes*. Randomly, a mole (or sometimes a power-up) appears in a hole. The player must click or tap the mole before it disappears.\n",
    "\n",
    "### Key Rules:\n",
    "- **Moles** give points when clicked.\n",
    "- **Power-ups** may give bonus points or extra time.\n",
    "- The game tracks **score** and saves the **high score** using local storage.\n",
    "\n",
    "This simple idea is perfect for studying OOP: each part of the game (holes, moles, power-ups, score) can be represented as an **object**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##  OOP Structure\n",
    "We will design the game using **classes**:\n",
    "\n",
    "- **`Game`** ‚Üí manages the entire program (composition).\n",
    "- **`Hole`** ‚Üí represents a place where something can appear.\n",
    "- **`Entity`** (abstract base class) ‚Üí shared logic for anything that appears in a hole.\n",
    "- **`Mole`** ‚Üí a specific type of `Entity`.\n",
    "- **`PowerUp`** ‚Üí another type of `Entity`.\n",
    "\n",
    "üëâ This is an example of **inheritance**: both `Mole` and `PowerUp` inherit from `Entity`.\n",
    "\n",
    "üëâ This is also **composition**: the `Game` is composed of multiple `Hole` objects."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##  UML Diagram (Visualizing OOP)\n",
    "\n",
    "<img src=\"{{site.baseurl}}/images/mermaid.png\" alt=\"img\">"
    "\n",
    "This diagram will show:\n",
    "- **Inheritance:** `Mole` and `PowerUp` extend `Entity`.\n",
    "- **Composition:** `Game` has multiple `Hole`s, each containing at most one `Entity`.\n",
    "- **Encapsulation:** each class controls its own data and behavior."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "##  Spawning Entities\n",
    "The game must randomly choose where to put new moles or power-ups. This is handled inside the `Game` class.\n",
    "\n",
    "Here is the method that chooses an empty hole and places something in it:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "spawnEntity() {\n",
    "    let emptyHoles = this.holes.filter(h => !h.entity);\n",
    "    if (emptyHoles.length > 0) {\n",
    "        let hole = emptyHoles[Math.floor(Math.random() * emptyHoles.length)];\n",
    "        if (Math.random() < 0.8) {\n",
    "            hole.entity = new Mole(hole, \"normal\");\n",
    "        } else {\n",
    "            hole.entity = new PowerUp(hole, \"bonus\");\n",
    "        }\n",
    "    }\n",
    "}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Teaching Explanation\n",
    "- `filter()` ‚Üí removes all holes that already have something inside.\n",
    "- `Math.random()` ‚Üí makes the game unpredictable.\n",
    "- If chance < 0.8, spawn a mole (80% chance). Otherwise, spawn a power-up (20% chance).\n",
    "\n",
    "üëâ Notice how the **Game class does not directly create pixels on screen**. Instead, it uses the object system: `Hole` manages its own location, `Entity` manages its own lifespan, etc."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### üìù FRQ Checkpoint 1\n",
    "**Prompt:**\n",
    "1. Explain why it is better for the `Game` class to delegate work to the `Hole` and `Entity` classes instead of doing everything itself.\n",
    "2. Modify the logic so that `GoldenMole` appears 5% of the time, worth double points.\n",
    "3. Justify how this change demonstrates **polymorphism**."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## üñ±Ô∏è Handling Player Input\n",
    "When a player clicks, the game checks whether the click intersects with a mole or power-up. If so, it calls the object‚Äôs `onHit()` method."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "handleClick(mx, my) {\n",
    "    this.holes.forEach(hole => {\n",
    "        if (hole.entity &&\n",
    "            mx >= hole.x - hole.size/2 && \n",
    "            mx <= hole.x + hole.size/2 &&\n",
    "            my >= hole.y - hole.size/2 &&\n",
    "            my <= hole.y + hole.size/2) {\n",
    "            hole.entity.onHit(this);\n",
    "        }\n",
    "    });\n",
    "}"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### Teaching Explanation\n",
    "- Each `Entity` object controls what happens when hit (encapsulation).\n",
    "- The `Game` just forwards the event.\n",
    "- **Polymorphism:** `onHit()` means something different for a `Mole` (gain points) versus a `PowerUp` (bonus effects)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "### üìù FRQ Checkpoint 2\n",
    "**Prompt:**\n",
    "1. Suppose the player clicks slightly outside the hole‚Äôs boundary. How does the code prevent counting that as a hit?\n",
    "2. Write pseudocode for a new entity `Bomb` that subtracts points when hit.\n",
